Coal occurs in four principal types, depending on the degree of coalification of the original vegetative source material. The lowest grade, lignite or brown coal, has the least heating content, lowest fixed carbon and higher volatile matter contents. Further coalification leads to the conversion of lignite to sub-bituminous coal, then to bituminous coal as the fixed carbon content and heating value increase. The final stage in coalification, to anthracite, produces a high heating-value, low volatile coal, typically with less than 10% volatile matter.

Used to differentiate between different qualities of bituminous coals. High-volatile bituminous grades through medium-volatile to low-volatile as the fixed carbon content and heating value increase with increasing rank.

Metallurgical coal is used to produce coke for steelmaking and other applications where its chemical properties are valuable as well as its heating capabilities. Thermal coal is burnt to raise steam, principally for electricity generation, but also for other industrial processes. PCI coal is used for pulverised coal injection in steelmaking, as a lower-cost replacement for metallurgical coke.
